[[File:Cortile della Pigna - lance mountain.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Fontana della Pigna (1st century AD)]] The '''Fontana della Pigna''' or simply Pigna ("The Pine cone") is a former [[Fountain#Ancient Roman fountains|Roman fountain]] which now decorates a vast niche in the wall of the Vatican facing the Cortile della Pigna, located in [[Vatican City]], in Rome, Italy.
==Description== Composed of a large [[bronze]] [[Conifer cone|pine cone]] almost four meters high which once spouted water from the top, the Pigna originally stood near the [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]] next to the [[Temple of Isis and Serapis|Temple of Isis]]. It was moved to the courtyard of the [[Old St. Peter's Basilica]] during the Middle Ages and then moved again, in 1608, to its present location.<ref>Official history on the Vatican website</ref>
The courtyard where it stands was originally part of the [[Cortile del Belvedere]], designed by [[Donato Bramante]] to connect the palace of [[Pope Innocent VIII]] with the [[Sistine Chapel]]. When Bramante died, architect [[Pirro Ligorio]] finished the project and added the wall and niche to close the courtyard. Construction of the [[Vatican Library]] divided the Cortile del Belvedere into two areas. The upper part of the courtyard, the Cortile della Pigna, takes its name from the fountain.
The bronze [[Peafowl|peacocks]] on either side of the fountain are copies of those decorating the tomb of the Emperor [[Hadrian]], now the [[Castel Sant'Angelo]]. The original peacocks are in the [[Vatican Museums#Sculpture museums|Braccio Nuovo Museum]].
==Rimini fountain== There is another fountain known as Fontana della Pigna in [[Rimini]], Italy, also of Ancient Roman origin but heavily restored. The pine cone sculpture crowning this fountain was only installed in 1807, replacing a 16th-century statue of [[Paul the Apostle|St. Paul]] damaged by the [[Napoleon]]ic army.
